---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import StepList from '../../../../../components/StepList.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Creating the Backlog" description="Set up Linear and generate an ordered backlog for Coastal Physio — infrastructure first, then migrations, then features.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Creating the Backlog</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Same process — architecture in, ordered tickets out. The critical difference: you create the backlog in Linear, not GitHub Projects. And the ordering has a new layer — infrastructure and migration tickets come before feature tickets.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Setting up Linear</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Linear is a project management tool used by many software teams. Free tier is sufficient for this project.</p>

  <StepList steps={[
    { title: "Create a Linear account", content: "Go to linear.app and sign up with your GitHub account." },
    { title: "Create a workspace", content: "Name it 'Coastal Physio' or similar. This is your project space." },
    { title: "Create a project", content: "Within the workspace, create a project for this build. Linear calls them 'Projects' — they're containers for related tickets." },
    { title: "Understand the workflow", content: "Linear uses statuses: Backlog, Todo, In Progress, Done. Same as GitHub Projects' columns. Drag tickets between statuses as you work." },
  ]} />

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Linear vs GitHub Projects:</strong> The underlying concept is identical — a list of tickets, ordered by priority, moving through workflow stages. Linear has a faster interface, keyboard shortcuts, and cycle tracking. GitHub Projects has tighter git integration. Neither is objectively better — they're different interfaces for the same workflow. The skill is managing a backlog, not operating a specific tool.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The prompt</h2>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Here is the PRD, design spec, and architecture for Coastal Physio:

[Paste your PRD here]
[Paste your design spec here]
[Paste your architecture here]

Create a BACKLOG.md with ordered tickets. Each ticket should have a title, description, and acceptance criteria checklist.

Critical ordering:
1. Infrastructure: RDS + ALB in Terraform (provision the database and load balancer first)
2. Alembic setup + initial migration (create the database schema)
3. Auth infrastructure (similar to P5 — user model, login, JWT, role middleware for patient/practitioner/admin)
4. Core features: patient registration, appointment booking, practitioner schedule
5. Clinical notes (depends on appointments and practitioner-patient relationships)
6. Admin features: manage bookings across locations, manage practitioners
7. Grafana setup and dashboards
8. Blue/green deployment pipeline

Infrastructure tickets MUST come before feature tickets — you can't build features without the database and load balancer.
Migration tickets come before the feature tickets that use those tables.
Each feature ticket should specify which Alembic migration it depends on.

Keep infrastructure, migration, and feature tickets separate. "Provision RDS" is NOT bundled with "Build appointment booking."
Keep auth tickets separate from feature tickets, as in P5.`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Review the backlog</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Infrastructure tickets come first</strong> — Terraform provisions RDS and ALB before any application work</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Alembic setup is its own ticket</strong> — configure Alembic, create the initial migration with core tables</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Auth before features</strong> — same principle as P5</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Migration dependencies are clear</strong> — each feature ticket notes which migration must be applied first</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Clinical notes come after appointments</strong> — notes are attached to appointments, so the appointment system must exist first</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Grafana and blue/green are near the end</strong> — monitoring and deployment pipeline after the application works</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">No ticket is too large</strong> — "Build appointment system" is too big. Break it into booking, viewing, cancelling, rescheduling.</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Once reviewed, create the tickets in Linear. Copy each ticket's title, description, and acceptance criteria. Set the priority order. This is your single source of truth for the build.</p>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: setup</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Backlog reviewed and in Linear. Set up the project.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/7/implementation/setup"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Setup →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
